### The Theory of General Relativity: A Comprehensive Overview

Published in 1915 by Albert Einstein, **General Relativity (GR)** is the second pillar of modern physics, succeeding Newton's law of universal gravitation. While Newton viewed gravity as an instantaneous force acting at a distance, Einstein revolutionized the concept by describing gravity not as a force, but as a geometric property of the universe.

At its core, General Relativity posits that **mass and energy curve the fabric of spacetime**, and that objects move along the straightest possible paths (geodesics) within this curved geometry.

---

### 1. Spacetime Curvature

In Newtonian physics, space and time are separate entities. In General Relativity, they are unified into a four-dimensional continuum called **spacetime**.

